Example \(\PageIndex{1}\) Solve \(2\sin ^{2} (t)+\sin (t)=0\) for all solutions with \(0\le t<2\pi\). Solution This equation kind of looks like a quadratic equation, but with sin( t ) in place of an algebraic variable (we often call such an equation “quadratic in sine”). As with all quadratic equations, we can use factoring techniques or the quadratic formula. This expression factors nicely, so we proceed by factoring out the common factor of sin(\(t\)): \[\sin (t)\left(2\sin (t)+1ight)=0
onumber\] Using the zero product theorem, we know that the product on the left will equal zero if either factor is zero, allowing us to break this equation into two cases: \[\sin (t)=0	ext{ or }2\sin (t)+1=0
onumber\] We can solve each of these equations independently, using our knowledge of special angles. \[\sin (t)=0
onumber\] \[2\sin (t)+1=0
onumber\] \[t = 0	ext{ or }t = \pi
onumber\] \[\sin (t)=-\dfrac{1}{2}
onumber\] \[t=\dfrac{7\pi }{6}	ext{ or }t=\dfrac{11\pi }{6}
onumber\] Together, this gives us four solutions to the equation on \(0\le t<2\pi\): \[t=0,\pi ,\dfrac{7\pi }{6} ,\dfrac{11\pi }{6}
onumber\] We could check these answers are reasonable by graphing the function and comparing the zeros.

Example \(\PageIndex{2}\) Solve \(3\sec ^{2} (t)-5\sec (t)-2=0\) for all solutions with \(0\le t<2\pi\). Solution Since the left side of this equation is quadratic in secant, we can try to factor it, and hope it factors nicely. If it is easier to for you to consider factoring without the trig function present, consider using a substitution \(u=\sec (t)\), resulting in \(3u^{2} -5u-2=0\), and then try to factor: \[3u^{2} -5u-2=(3u+1)(u-2)
onumber\] Undoing the substitution, \[(3\sec (t)+1)(\sec (t)-2)=0
onumber\] Since we have a product equal to zero, we break it into the two cases and solve each separately. \[3\sec (t)+1=0
onumber\]Isolate the secant \[\sec (t)=-\dfrac{1}{3}
onumber\]Rewrite as a cosine \[\dfrac{1}{\cos (t)} =-\dfrac{1}{3}
onumber\]Invert both sides \[\cos (t)=-3
onumber\] Since the cosine has a range of [-1, 1], the cosine will never take on an output of -3. There are no solutions to this case. Continuing with the second case, \[\sec (t)-2=0
onumber\]Isolate the secant \[\sec (t)=2
onumber\]Rewrite as a cosine \[\dfrac{1}{\cos (t)} =2
onumber\]Invert both sides \[\cos (t)=\dfrac{1}{2}
onumber\]This gives two solutions \[t=\dfrac{\pi }{3}	ext{ or }t=\dfrac{5\pi }{3}
onumber\] These are the only two solutions on the interval. By utilizing technology to graph \(f(t)=3\sec ^{2} (t)-5\sec (t)-2\), a look at a graph confirms there are only two zeros for this function on the interval [0, 2 \(\pi\)), which assures us that we didn’t miss anything.

