In this section, we begin expanding our repertoire of trigonometric identities. The sum and difference identities \[\cos (\alpha - eta )=\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )\] \[\cos (\alpha + eta )=\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )\] \[\sin (\alpha + eta )=\sin (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\cos (\alpha )\sin ( eta )\] \[\sin (\alpha - eta )=\sin (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-\cos (\alpha )\sin ( eta )\] We will prove the difference of angles identity for cosine. The rest of the identities can be derived from this one. Proof of the difference of angles identity for cosine Consider two points on a unit circle: \(P\) at an angle of \(\alpha\) from the positive \(x\) axis with coordinates \(\left(\cos (\alpha ),\sin (\alpha )ight)\), and \(Q\) at an angle of \( eta\) with coordinates \(\left(\cos ( eta ),\sin ( eta)ight)\). Notice the measure of angle \(POQ\) is \(\alpha\) – \( eta\). Label two more points: \(C\) at an angle of \(\alpha\) – \( eta\), with coordinates \(\left(\cos (\alpha - eta ),\sin (\alpha - eta )ight)\), \(D\) at the point (1, 0). Notice that the distance from \(C\) to \(D\) is the same as the distance from \(P\) to \(Q\) because triangle \(COD\) is a rotation of triangle \(POQ\). Using the distance formula to find the distance from \(P\) to \(Q\) yields \[\sqrt{\left(\cos (\alpha )-\cos ( eta )ight)^{2} +\left(\sin (\alpha )-\sin ( eta )ight)^{2} }
onumber\] Expanding this \[\sqrt{\cos ^{2} (\alpha )-2\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\cos ^{2} ( eta )+\sin ^{2} (\alpha )-2\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )+\sin ^{2} ( eta )}
onumber\] Applying the Pythagorean Identity and simplifying \[\sqrt{2-2\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-2\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )}
onumber\] Similarly, using the distance formula to find the distance from \(C\) to \(D\) \[\sqrt{\left(\cos (\alpha - eta )-1ight)^{2} +\left(\sin (\alpha - eta )-0ight)^{2} }
onumber\] Expanding this \[\sqrt{\cos ^{2} (\alpha - eta )-2\cos (\alpha - eta )+1+\sin ^{2} (\alpha - eta )}
onumber\] Applying the Pythagorean Identity and simplifying \[\sqrt{-2\cos (\alpha - eta )+2}
onumber\] Since the two distances are the same we set these two formulas equal to each other and simplify \[\sqrt{2-2\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-2\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )} =\sqrt{-2\cos (\alpha - eta )+2}
onumber\] \[2-2\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-2\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )=-2\cos (\alpha - eta )+2
onumber\] \[\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )=\cos (\alpha - eta )
onumber\] This establishes the identity. Exercise \(\PageIndex{1}\) By writing \(\cos (\alpha + eta )\) as \(\cos \left(\alpha -\left(- eta ight)ight)\), show the sum of angles identity for cosine follows from the difference of angles identity proven above. \[ egin{array}{l} {\cos (\alpha + eta )=\cos (\alpha -(- eta ))} \ {\cos (\alpha )\cos (- eta )+\sin (\alpha )\sin (- eta )} \ {\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )+\sin (\alpha )(-\sin ( eta ))} \ {\cos (\alpha )\cos ( eta )-\sin (\alpha )\sin ( eta )} \end{array}
onumber\] The sum and difference of angles identities are often used to rewrite expressions in other forms, or to rewrite an angle in terms of simpler angles. Exercise \(\PageIndex{2}\) Find the exact value of \(\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi }{12} ight)\). \[\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi }{12} ight)=\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi }{3} -\dfrac{\pi }{4} ight)=\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi }{3} ight)\cos \left(\dfrac{\pi }{4} ight)-\cos \left(\dfrac{\pi }{3} ight)\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi }{4} ight)
onumber\] \[=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2} \dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} -\dfrac{1}{2} \dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2}\quad \dfrac{\sqrt{6} -\sqrt{2} }{4}
onumber\] Additionally, these identities can be used to simplify expressions or prove new identities These identities can also be used to solve equations.

