Example \(\PageIndex{1}\) Find the exact value of \(\cos (75{}^\circ )\). Solution Since \(75{}^\circ =30{}^\circ +45{}^\circ\), we can evaluate \(\cos (75{}^\circ )\) as \[\cos (75{}^\circ )=\cos (30{}^\circ +45{}^\circ )
onumber\] Apply the cosine sum of angles identity \[=\cos (30{}^\circ )\cos (45{}^\circ )-\sin (30{}^\circ )\sin (45{}^\circ )
onumber\] Evaluate \[=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2} \cdot \dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2} -\dfrac{1}{2} \cdot \dfrac{\sqrt{2} }{2}
onumber\] Simply \[=\dfrac{\sqrt{6} -\sqrt{2} }{4}
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{3}\) Prove \(\dfrac{\sin (a+b)}{\sin (a-b)} =\dfrac{	an (a)+	an (b)}{	an (a)-	an (b)}\). Solution As with any identity, we need to first decide which side to begin with. Since the left side involves sum and difference of angles, we might start there \[\dfrac{\sin (a+b)}{\sin (a-b)}
onumber\] Apply the sum and difference of angle identities \[=\dfrac{\sin (a)\cos (b)+\cos (a)\sin (b)}{\sin (a)\cos (b)-\cos (a)\sin (b)}
onumber\] Since it is not immediately obvious how to proceed, we might start on the other side, and see if the path is more apparent. \[\dfrac{	an (a)+	an (b)}{	an (a)-	an (b)}
onumber\] Rewriting the tangents using the tangent identity \[=\dfrac{\dfrac{\sin (a)}{\cos (a)} +\dfrac{\sin (b)}{\cos (b)} }{\dfrac{\sin (a)}{\cos (a)} -\dfrac{\sin (b)}{\cos (b)} }
onumber\]Multiplying the top and bottom by cos(\(a\))cos(\(b\)) \[=\dfrac{\left(\dfrac{\sin (a)}{\cos (a)} +\dfrac{\sin (b)}{\cos (b)} ight)\cos (a)\cos (b)}{\left(\dfrac{\sin (a)}{\cos (a)} -\dfrac{\sin (b)}{\cos (b)} ight)\cos (a)\cos (b)}
onumber\]Distributing and simplifying \[=\dfrac{\sin (a)\cos (b)+\sin (b)\cos (a)}{\sin (a)\cos (b)-\sin (b)\cos (a)}
onumber\]From above, we recognize this \[=\dfrac{\sin (a+b)}{\sin (a-b)}
onumber\]Establishing the identity

Example \(\PageIndex{4}\) Solve \(\sin (x)\sin (2x)+\cos (x)\cos (2x)=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}\). Solution By recognizing the left side of the equation as the result of the difference of angles identity for cosine, we can simplify the equation \[\sin (x)\sin (2x)+\cos (x)\cos (2x)=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}
onumber\]Apply the difference of angles identity \[\cos (x-2x)=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}
onumber\] \[\cos (-x)=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}
onumber\]Use the negative angle identity \[\cos (x)=\dfrac{\sqrt{3} }{2}
onumber\] Since this is a special cosine value we recognize from the unit circle, we can quickly write the answers: \[ egin{array}{l} {x=\dfrac{\pi }{6} +2\pi k} \ {x=\dfrac{11\pi }{6} +2\pi k} \end{array}
onumber\], where \(k\) is an integer

